    <mainmatter>
      <chapter xml:id="chap-introduction">
      <title>Introduction</title>
      <section xml:id="what-is-an-ordinary-differential-equation">
      <title>What is an Ordinary Differential Equation?</title>
      <p>Let&#x27;s begin with an example. Consider the function <m> y= f(x) = x^2</m>  on the interval <m>(-1, 1).</m> We know that <m>f</m> is differentiable on <m>(-1, 1)</m> with its first order derivative &lt;me xml:id=&quot;chap1-1&quot;&gt; \frac{dy}{dx} =2x. &lt;/me&gt; If we treat (<xref ref="chap1-1"/>) as an equation with <m> y </m> as the unknown, then we see that the function <m> y = x^2 </m> satisfies the equation, and therefore  <m> y = x^2 </m> is  a solution of (<xref ref="chap1-1"/>) on the interval <m> (-1, 1) </m>. The equation (<xref ref="chap1-1"/>) serves as an example of an <em>ordinary differential equation</em> which involves a function of one independent variable and  ordinary derivatives of the function.</p>
      <p>A classical example of an ordinary differential equation is Newton’s law of gravity, which states that <em>an object  in a free fall from a point near the Earth's surface experiences a constant acceleration, assuming air resistance is negligible</em>. This motion is described mathematically by the differential equation &lt;me xml:id=&quot;chap1-3&quot;&gt; \frac{d^2x}{dt^2} = g, &lt;/me&gt; where <m> g </m> represents the gravitational acceleration near the Earth&#x27;s surface, and <m> x = x(t) </m> denotes the object&#x27;s height above the ground as a function of time <m>t</m>. Equivalently, the object  of mass <m>m</m> experiences a constant weight while near Earth’s surface described by &lt;me xml:id=&quot;chap1-4&quot;&gt; m\frac{d^2x}{dt^2} = mg. &lt;/me&gt; In order to make this motion a little bit more realistic, suppose that air exerts  a resisting force  proportional to the velocity of the object.  With this assumption,  the differential equation (<xref ref="chap1-4"/>) of  motion becomes</p>
      <p>\begin{equation*} m\frac{d^2x}{dt^2} = mg- \beta\, \frac{dx}{dt}, \end{equation*} where <m>\beta>0</m> denotes the constant of proportionality of the air resistance to the velocity. Rearranging the terms and setting <m>b=\beta/m,</m> we have \begin{equation*} \frac{d^2x}{dt^2}+ b\, \frac{dx}{dt}= g, \end{equation*} that is, &lt;me xml:id=&quot;chap1-5&quot;&gt; x&amp;#x27;&amp;#x27;(t)+ b \, x&amp;#x27;(t)= g. &lt;/me&gt; Let <m>v(t)</m> denote <m>x'(t),</m> the velocity of the object.  Then (<xref ref="chap1-5"/>) can also be expressed as  the following system of differential equations: &lt;me xml:id=&quot;chap1-6&quot;&gt; \begin{cases} x&amp;#x27;(t) =v(t),\\ v&amp;#x27;(t)+ b\, v(t)= g. \end{cases} &lt;/me&gt; We will study more systems of ordinary differential equations in Chapter~<xref ref="Systems"/>.</p>
      <subsection xml:id="definitions-and-vocabulary">
      <title>Definitions and Vocabulary</title>
      <p>Suppose we are given the differential equation (<xref ref="chap1-1"/>) and asked to find all functions   <m>y</m> with derivative equal to <m>2x</m>. To answer this, we  use the <em>fundamental theorem of calculus</em> on the interval <m>[0, t]</m> with <m>t\in (-1, 1)</m> and integrate both sides of (<xref ref="chap1-1"/>)  to obtain &lt;me&gt; f(t) =\int_0^t \frac{dy}{dx} \, dx = \int_0^t 2x\, dx = t^2 + C, &lt;/me&gt; where  <m>C</m> denotes an arbitrary  real constant. Renaming <m>t</m> as <m>x,</m>  we find that <m>f(x) = x^2 +C,</m>   and we see that for each value of <m>C</m> the function <m>y = x^2+C</m> has  derivative equal to <m>2x</m> for all <m>x</m> in <m>(-1, 1).</m>   The collection of functions given by &lt;me xml:id=&quot;chap1-7&quot;&gt; y = x^2+C, &lt;/me&gt; one function for each value of <m>C</m>, comprises all solutions of the equation (<xref ref="chap1-1"/>). The collection (<xref ref="chap1-7"/>) is called the <em>general solution</em> of (<xref ref="chap1-1"/>) and each member of (<xref ref="chap1-7"/>) corresponding to a specific value of <m>C</m> is called a <em>particular solution</em> of (<xref ref="chap1-1"/>). The concepts of particular and general solutions apply to all differential equations discussed in this book and will be used consistently without further explanation.</p>
      <p><m>\bullet</m> DEs, solutions, domain of solutions, goal future predictions or long-term behavior of dependent variables, why intervals are so important for solutions?\\ <m>\bullet</m> Emphasis on the rate of change of a quantity both mathematically and geometrically.</p>
      </subsection>
